#14203
@@bSouthern Tidal Entry@@N~
@@bThe ground descends sharply into a tidal depression here, where the Saltglass Reach's mineral surface becomes waterlogged and treacherous at high tide.@@N The soil is a grey-brown clay shot through with coils of dried seagrass, and the surface cracks under foot pressure in ways that suggest shallow standing water just beneath. Small mounds of excavated sand mark @@btidemouth crab burrows@@N distributed across the flat at regular intervals, each surrounded by a scatter of shell chip debris. @@lThe flat smells of sulphur, salt, and the particular sweetness of decomposing seagrass.@@N Deeper into the flat, the ground shimmers with what might be thin standing water or might be flat-surface heat distortion — it is impossible to tell from a distance.
