@@yTide Ledger Hall@@N~
@@yThe Tide Ledger Hall is the largest and most authoritative of Mafdet's four Ledger Houses — the official custodian of the Saltweight standard, the certifying authority for all harbor-measure conversions, and the first point of arbitration for cargo disputes.@@N The Hall's main chamber is vast for the Ledger Quarter: a double-height room with a gallery level, its walls covered in reference scales from floor to ceiling — bronze weight sets, calibrated measure rods, and conversion charts in multiple script systems. @@yThe master weight set occupies a central display case: seven bronze reference measures of descending size, each certified by the Great Oasis Measure Authority and marked with a triple-seal validation stamp.@@N Archive clerks move between the gallery and main floor retrieving specific historical manifests on request, their familiarity with the filing system visible in the efficiency of their movement. The Hall also maintains the current conversion-ratio board that is copied each week to the Market of the Shoreward Tables. @@lThe Tide Ledger Hall's authority extends across all four Ledger Houses by virtue of holding the primary Saltweight standard; the other three Houses certify against its master weights.@@N Littoral Branch notation marks on the gallery columns indicate this building's original function as a coastal survey archive before the Shoreward Compact reorganised the Ledger Quarter's hierarchy.
