#14305
@@lHarbor Gate@@N~
@@lThe Harbor Gate of Mafdet opens the full cove to view — not a military gate but a commercial threshold, a wide stone archway whose passage marks the moment when the city's documentary bureaucracy yields to the physical reality of maritime operations.@@N The cove is immediately ahead: a natural basin reinforced with stone breakwaters on the northern and southern arms, the harbor chain's iron links arcing across the mouth from the Signal Tower to the Tidewall anchor point. @@lTide and weather have shaped the stone of the harbor front into organic curves that no architect planned — the basalt lower courses of every building are smoothed by spray and stained with mineral deposits in colours ranging from pale ochre to deep green.@@N The harbor smells of salt, tar, rope hemp, and the particular sweetness of wet timber that has been alternately soaked and dried for decades. The sound of commercial loading is constant: shouted cargo calls, the creak of block-and-tackle, and the rhythmic strike of cargo hooks against wooden crate sides. @@lThe Harbor Healer's Station is accessible to the south — a permanent triage point for the injuries that dock work produces at a frequency the city has long since accepted as operational background.@@N The northern pier arm extends into the cove from here; the harbor front proper runs south toward the signal tower and eventually the Tidewall.
