@@lThe approach road to the North Pier runs along the harbor front's northern arm, its surface a mix of stone paving and compacted cargo debris — rope ends, spilled salt, wood shavings, and the occasional dropped cargo label.@@N The smell of the harbor is strongest here: bilge water, treated hemp rope, tar caulking, and the particular smell of wet wool that working sailors carry permanently. @@lThe Strand Folk basalt foundations of the original pier structure are visible at the waterline — darker stone, more precisely fitted than the later construction above them, and noticeably eroded into smooth curves by decades of tidal contact.@@N Harbor workers move cargo here in a continuous chain, the loading rhythm as familiar and persistent as the sound of the waves.
