@@lThe breakwater causeway is a narrow stone path extending east from the harbor front, built atop the breakwater's mass to provide access to the deep-water inspection point at the breakwater's end.@@N The causeway is barely wide enough for two people to pass each other if both lean slightly toward the water — a constraint that creates a social navigation challenge when cargo movement is underway. @@lThe water is visible on both sides: the calmer harbor basin to the north and the more exposed approach water to the south.@@N Sea spray reaches the causeway surface constantly, keeping the stone wet and slippery, and the footing requires attention even for experienced harbor workers. The breakwater itself rises below the causeway path, its stone face barnacle-encrusted and wave-scored.
