@@lBreakwater End@@N~
@@lThe breakwater's furthest point is a small stone platform exposed on three sides to open water — the harbor basin to the north, the approach channel to the south, and the open sea directly east.@@N From here, the full sweep of the cove is visible: the harbor chain in its raised position spanning the harbor mouth from this point to the Signal Tower; the two pier arms extending into the basin from the northern and southern harbor front; the Shrine Terrace's basalt platform visible above the city's roofline to the northwest. @@lThe sea beyond the chain shows its depth immediately — the bright coastal shallows transition within a short distance to the deep blue of open water.@@N The breakwater end bears a bronze inspection fitting where Harbor Warden chain-monitors attach their measurement equipment for daily chain-integrity checks. The fitting itself carries the chain's northern mid-span support, and when the chain is raised, it is possible to reach out and touch the iron links from this platform. @@lThe sound here is simply the sea — wind, wave, and the creak of the chain at its attachment point.@@N The platform has no shelter of any kind; weather that reaches the harbor mouth reaches the breakwater end unmodified.
