@@gTidewall Walk, Northern End@@N~
@@gThe Tidewall's northern end is where the harbor district's southward curve meets the seaward defensive perimeter — the transition from commercial harbor to institutional wall defining Mafdet's seaward boundary.@@N The wall is the oldest continuously maintained structure in the city, its lower courses cut from the same dark basalt as the Strand Folk approach markers in the Tidemouth Dunes, predating the Compact's harbor expansion by generations of charter authority. @@gBarnacle encrustation covers the seaward face to nearly two body-lengths, the tideline of exceptional storms preserved in white calcium deposits at irregular intervals above the wash zone.@@N The wall-walk extends southward along the Tidewall's length — wide enough for two people abreast, the seaward face dropping steeply to the exterior shingle below and the inner face presenting the sealed backs of residential buildings to any observer on the walk. @@gSalt mist drifts in from the east when wind drives from open water, coating exposed stone and clothing with a thin crystalline deposit within minutes.@@N
