@@gTidewall Residences, Shell-Inlay Court@@N~
@@gThe Shell-Inlay Court is the Tidewall's most visually distinctive residential precinct — the facade work here is more elaborate and better preserved than anywhere else on the wall-walk, the Strand Folk decorative tradition maintained by families whose shellwork skills pass from parent to child as a community obligation.@@N Beacon sconces of salt-glazed ceramic are mounted at regular intervals along the interior wall face, their reflector plates designed to cast light along the wall-walk and down into the residential court below. @@gThe patterns in the shell-inlay work use a consistent grammar: horizontal bands of cockle representing tidal height, vertical runs of periwinkle marking seasonal boundaries, and single rows of red oyster shell at the level of the highest remembered storm.@@N A lintel stone at the precinct's northern edge bears a Strand Folk inscription — the oldest readable notation in this section of the wall, identifying this as the court of those who remember what the water answered. @@gThe beacon sconces are still lit at dusk by whoever is first home to the court, a maintained custom predating the Strandline Compact's authority in the city.@@N
