@@gStrand Rememberer's Alcove@@N~
@@gThe alcove is a dedicated space maintained by the Strand Rememberers — the oldest practitioner's hall on the Tidewall, its walls covered in navigation song tablets, flat stone slabs inscribed with the coastal approach sequences that Strand Folk pilots used before written charts replaced oral tradition.@@N The Strand Rememberer who keeps this alcove is among the most senior practitioners remaining, a guardian of oral cartography in a city that has largely transitioned to Littoral Branch written documentation. @@gThe navigation songs inscribed on the tablets are functional memory tools, each sequence encoding the tidal approach to a specific coastal landmark in a format that can be learned by ear and recalled under stress.@@N The guardian origin stories of the Strand Folk are also kept here, separate from the navigation tablets on a lower shelf of smoothed basalt — the earliest-layer accounts of the agreement between coastal communities and the city-building traditions that created Mafdet's jurisdictional framework. @@gThe alcove smells of salt, old stone, and the beeswax used to protect the tablet surfaces from moisture.@@N
